@ancestors ["UKRN WP draft-16-april §3 Pattern (prior predictive; credible intervals; top VoI targets; VoI vs saliency; explicit Tension/Composition/Check; paper baseline position favouring VoI-first)" "UKRN WP §4 'Where uncertainty lives, where attention lives' (VoI vs saliency contrast)" "T1 instrument (5 behaviour-change indicators; ethics approved)" "equity/visible-impact (monitoring-chain failure this design pattern answers at selection scale)" "Bayesian value-of-information theory (decision-theoretic foundation)" "Ostrom (1990) — monitoring chain across action arenas"]

! conclusion: A service with limited evaluation capacity should measure where the next observation is most likely to matter.  Sometimes that means measuring where the evidence gap is biggest.  Sometimes it means measuring where board attention, funder attention, or sector attention is already concentrated.  The key discipline is to choose deliberately and to say which principle is selecting the next wave of work.  Measurement should not drift toward whatever is easiest, most flattering, or most familiar.

  + context: The current paper makes two things clear.  First, some open-research indicators can already be measured reasonably well, while others still cannot.  Second, the wider sector conversation and funder cycle do not attend evenly to every topic, institution type, or signal.  Because evaluation capacity is bounded, UKRN Services cannot treat every possible question as equally urgent.  It needs a rule for deciding where the next piece of measurement effort goes.

  + IF:
    The pattern operates on the axis: uncertainty reduction ↔ stakeholder attention.
    Irreducible: the place where the service is least sure is not always the place where outside attention is already waiting.  A single wave of evaluation often has to choose which question it is trying to answer first.

  + HOWEVER:
    Real costs: measuring where uncertainty is highest sharpens the design fastest, but it may miss the places where visible accountability is most needed.  Measuring where attention already sits may help with governance, legitimacy, and partnership, but it may tell the service little that it does not broadly know already.
    Active dynamic: both maps move.  Uncertainty should shrink if the service is learning.  Attention should shift as sector priorities, funder cycles, and public pressures change.  So the selection rule cannot be fixed once and forgotten.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Convenience drift: the same easy-to-reach settings are measured repeatedly because they are easy
      - Reassurance drift: measurement is aimed mainly at places most likely to produce good news
      - Uncertainty neglect: the service keeps talking confidently about areas it still has weak evidence on
      - Attention neglect: the service learns things internally but cannot answer the questions external stakeholders actually ask
      - Hidden mix: a wave is really selected on mixed grounds, but only one reason is published
      - Measure-everything fiction: a bounded service pretends it can observe everything at once and ends up observing none of it well

  + THEN: Choose the selection principle for each wave before the work starts, and publish it.
    + COMPOSITIONS:
      (1) Uncertainty-first: use the wave mainly to tighten the weakest parts of the evidence base.  Gives up some immediate external legibility.
      (2) Attention-first: use the wave mainly to answer the question that funders, partners, or member institutions are already pressing on.  Gives up some learning efficiency.
      (3) Split wave: reserve part of the budget for the biggest evidence gaps and part for the most watched questions.  Gives up some reach in order to do both honestly.
      These compositions are not ranked in the abstract.  The current paper leans toward uncertainty-first when the aim is to improve the design, but it also makes clear that attention cannot simply be ignored.

    + CHECK:
      Engaged when: each evaluation wave has a stated reason for selection; the service can say which open question or implementation decision the wave is meant to inform; the next wave reflects what the last one learned.
      Failing when: measurement choices are made post hoc; the same terrain is measured repeatedly for convenience; or no one can explain why this wave happened here rather than somewhere else.

  + BECAUSE:
    Indicator capacity is uneven: The paper is explicit that some indicators are already tractable and some are not.  That means measurement discipline is not a luxury.  It is how the service avoids promising to demonstrate things it still cannot actually demonstrate.

    Learning depends on selective observation: If evidence is supposed to shape design, then the service has to decide where an additional observation will change its judgement most.  Otherwise evaluation becomes diffuse activity rather than decision support.

    External attention is real: Member institutions, funders, and partners do not care about all questions equally.  A service that never measures where scrutiny already sits may become internally coherent but externally unpersuasive.

    Governance benefit: Stating the selection principle before fieldwork makes the service's reasoning inspectable.  It allows institutions and partners to challenge not only the findings, but the choice of what was measured in the first place.

    Mechanic, in short:
    Derived from the paper's distinction between what can currently be measured, where uncertainty still lives, and where sector attention already sits.
    Answers the service-level version of the visible-impact problem: not just whether evidence exists, but where the service chooses to look next.
    Mapped to the learning loop at the measure step: after diagnosis and provisioning, bounded evaluation effort is placed where it will matter most.
    Coordination requirement: Medium, rising when a wave depends on distributed data collection across institutions.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Publish, for each evaluation wave, whether it is mainly uncertainty-reducing, attention-facing, or a stated mix
    - Tie each wave explicitly to one of the paper's open questions or implementation decisions
    - Reassess the selection rule after each wave rather than repeating the same pattern by habit
    - Keep a visible list of questions the service still cannot yet measure well, so silence is not mistaken for closure
    - Use this pattern upstream of design revision, where evidence is meant to produce operational consequence
